“How Can the Government 'Take Back' a City It Largely Controls?” is an article in the New York Times berating the federal government for not giving autonomy to the elected Washington, D.C. officials to govern and beautify the city. The graphs of property owned by the government were helpful, along with the pictures of repairs needed to city fountains and RFK stadium, as they showed the wide range of ownership the federal government has in the town. The Short Story analogy, dating back to 1783 and the founding fathers of America, was a bit trivial, as it really doesn’t relate to current times, as no laws were established to enforce what they wanted. It would be better to find a source that is working with the Federal Government towards the beautification of WASH DC and the report on the plan.
